msgstr ""

# header
#: instructor-training/_extras/guide.md:155
msgid "### General tips for online training:  "
msgstr ""

# unordered list
#: instructor-training/_extras/guide.md:156
msgid "- **Support the lead**"
msgstr ""

# unordered list
#: instructor-training/_extras/guide.md:157
msgid ""
"\t- It's tempting to check-out and check email/do work when your co-teacher "
"has taken the wheel.  Try not to do this!  Ways that you can support your "
"co-teacher when they are leading are:"
msgstr ""

# unordered list
#: instructor-training/_extras/guide.md:158
msgid "\t  - Monitor the chat in zoom/notes"
msgstr ""

# unordered list
#: instructor-training/_extras/guide.md:159
msgid "\t  - Help post exercises + provide instructions"
msgstr ""

# unordered list
#: instructor-training/_extras/guide.md:160
msgid "\t  - Find links or references"
msgstr ""

# unordered list
#: instructor-training/_extras/guide.md:161
msgid ""
"\t- Make sure that whomever is actively teaching always has host privileges."
" When you take turns instructing, remember to hand-off host privileges "
"during the change-over."
msgstr ""

# unordered list
#: instructor-training/_extras/guide.md:162
msgid "- **Exercise management**"
msgstr ""

# unordered list
#: instructor-training/_extras/guide.md:163
msgid ""
"  - After the first exercise, keep a list of all the participants in a plain"
" text file on your computer so can you can easily paste it into the shared "
"note-taking doc for exercises. This way, everyone immediately has a place to"
" start writing.(G.W.) Tip: randomise the order of names every once in a "
"while so it is not always the same person that is first or last in the list,"
" and thus may get more or less attention when you discuss the responses "
"(LN.)"
msgstr ""

# unordered list
#: instructor-training/_extras/guide.md:164
msgid ""
"  - Screen-share a timer/countdown clock (like [this timer from "
"timeanddate.com](https://www.timeanddate.com/timer/)) so participants know "
"how long they have to work on exercises. (L.N)"
msgstr ""

# unordered list
#: instructor-training/_extras/guide.md:165
msgid "- **Shared notes tips**"
msgstr ""

# unordered list
#: instructor-training/_extras/guide.md:166
msgid ""
"  - No matter what kind of shared doc you are using, it's usually a good "
"idea to create"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_extras/guide.md:167
msgid ""
"  two documents -- one for each day of the training.  \n"
"    - Suggestion from AN: create a third doc for sharing concept maps, since they are\n"
"    images and can slow down the document.  \n"
"  - Etherpad pros + cons\n"
"    - Pros: line numbers\n"
"    - Cons: simple formatting\n"
"  - Google Doc pros + cons\n"
"    - Pros: richer formatting\n"
"    - Cons: no line numbers\n"
"- **Zoom tips**\n"
"  - Announce *at the beginning* of the training that all participants should mute when\n"
"  they are not talking.  You may need to repeat this a few times during the early part\n"
"  of the training, until people are doing it consistently.  \n"
"  - In general, it works best to have everyone use zoom individually on their computers\n"
"  (so you can see everyone's faces); for trainings where some of the participants are\n"
"  co-located, have them use their own computer for video but pick one person to use\n"
"  for mic/sound.  \n"
"  - “Gallery view” in the upper right toggles the display to show more participants' videos.  \n"
"  - “Share screen” is at the bottom middle of the screen. To end “share screen”, click the red button that will appear at the top middle of the screen when you are in screen sharing mode.  \n"
"  - When you screen share, you have the option to share individual apps or your entire desktop. The default is the full desktop.\n"
"  - The Zoom chat is not stable (it is not saved across sessions or after going into breakout rooms, and people who have just joined a room can't see previously posted chat items). We highly recommend using the Etherpad or Google Doc chat instead. For those who want to save the chat, they do that using the \"More\" option in the chat window, which offers \"Save chat\". Choosing this will save the chat to a local text file on the person's computer.\n"
"  - During breaks, learners will often turn off their video and wait for your audio cue to re-activate. This makes it look like no one is back from break, but just saying 'hello' will generally get a bunch of people to come back on video quickly.\n"
"  - When several attendees are in the same room (member trainings): it is helpful to have every participant log in separately so that you can see names and faces and they can interact by waving or using the chat. However, it is important that only one microphone and speaker should be active in the room at one time or feedback and noise will be a problem. When creating breakouts, you can either leave these people in the main room or shuffle people around to create a room just for them. Either way, ask them to leave a mic on so you can listen in.\n"
"  - Attendees might like to have a separate room (without Trainers) to network in over lunch or other breaks. Be prepared to assign that room and then close it to restart the main session.\n"
"  - when you are in the Zoom meeting room but unintentionally not as the host, look for the button 'Claim host' (click on the 'Participants' button; you'll be asked for a 6-digit host key, which you can find (after logging in to [Zoom][zoom-home]), at the bottom of the profile, see [the explanation here][zoom-host-key]."
msgstr ""

